````markdown
# üìå Proyecto: Integraci√≥n de ESP32, Mosquitto e InfluxDB

## üìù Descripci√≥n
Este proyecto tiene como objetivo la integraci√≥n de una **ESP32**, un **servidor Mosquitto (MQTT)** y **InfluxDB** para el almacenamiento y visualizaci√≥n de datos provenientes del **bus CAN de una moto el√©ctrica**.

La ESP32 act√∫a como **nodo de adquisici√≥n**, recibiendo tramas CAN de diferentes componentes, como la ECU y el BMS. Estas tramas se env√≠an mediante **MQTT** a un servidor Mosquitto y posteriormente se almacenan en InfluxDB mediante un cliente Python. La informaci√≥n es procesada y organizada en **measurements** dentro de un **bucket** en InfluxDB.

Para la visualizaci√≥n de los datos, utilizamos **Grafana**, donde se dise√±ar√°n dashboards personalizados para analizar el estado del veh√≠culo en tiempo real.
````

````markdown
üìê **Formato de la trama CAN almacenada en InfluxDB**:
```plaintext
ID (4 bytes)      TIMESTAMP (8 bytes)      PAYLOAD (8 bytes)
"0CF11E05"  +  "00000195e0fdc5ee"  +  "05000000C3010000"
```
- **ID**: Identifica el dispositivo y tipo de mensaje.
- **TIMESTAMP**: Reemplazado por el timestamp actual al insertarse en InfluxDB.
- **PAYLOAD**: Datos a procesar seg√∫n el tipo de componente.

‚ö†Ô∏è **Cualquier error de formato har√° que el mensaje sea descartado.**
````

````markdown
# üìå Proyecto: Integraci√≥n de ESP32, Mosquitto e InfluxDB
````

````markdown
## üóÑÔ∏è Base de datos
Usamos **InfluxDB** como base de datos NoSQL para almacenar tramas del protocolo CAN de la moto. Las tramas llegan por MQTT y se insertan mediante un cliente de Python.

üìê **Estructura del bucket `udmt` en InfluxDB:**
```plaintext
Bucket (udmt):
    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Measurement (ECU):
    ‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Point: Definir tramas de la ECU
    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Measurement (BMS):
    ‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Point: Definir tramas de la BMS
```
üìå **Ejemplo de `Point` en la medida `ECU`**:
```plaintext
Measurement: ECU
    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Point: rpm=3200, temperatura_motor=90, timestamp=1711190400000
    ...
````

```python
class DBManager:

    def writePoint(self, measurement:str, timestamp:int = None,**kwargs):
        """
        Writes a point to the InfluxDB database
        The format is as follows:
        Measurement: <measurement>
        Tag: tag_<tag_name> = <tag_value> // The tag_ will be removed when writing the tag
        Field: <field_name> = <field_value>
        """
        try:
            p = influxdb_client.Point(measurement)

            # MotoStudent Bike Signature
            p.tag("Moto", "moto_student_2025")

            if timestamp is not None:
                # if(len(timestamp) != 8 ):
                #     print(f"Error, timestamp format is not 8 byte: {timestamp}")
                #     return False
                # else:
                p.time(timestamp, write_precision="ms")

            for key in kwargs:
                if key.startswith("tag_"):
                    p.tag(key[4:], kwargs[key])
                else:
                    p.field(key, kwargs[key])
            self.write_api.write(bucket = self.bucket, org = self.org, record=p)
            #...
```

```python
            timestamp = struct.unpack(">Q", data[4:12])[0]  #If the timestamp is not recent, the message will not be added to the db
```

```yaml
services:
  mosquitto:
    image: eclipse-mosquitto:latest
    ports:
      - "2000:1883"
    volumes:
      - ./mosquitto/config:/mosquitto/config
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD", "sh", "-c", "nc -z 0.0.0.0 1883 || exit 1"]
      interval: 5s
      timeout: 3s
      retries: 3
      start_period: 5s
  
  esp32-server:
    build: ./server
    depends_on:
      mosquitto:
        condition: service_healthy
      db:
        condition: service_healthy
  
  db:
    image: influxdb:latest
    ports:
      - "8086:8086"
    volumes:
      - ./db/data:/var/lib/influxdb2
    environment:
      - DOCKER_INFLUXDB_INIT_MODE=setup
      - DOCKER_INFLUXDB_INIT_USERNAME=admin
      - DOCKER_INFLUXDB_INIT_PASSWORD=adminadmin
```

````UNKNOWN

This directory is intended for project header files.

A header file is a file containing C declarations and macro definitions
to be shared between several project source files. You request the use of a
header file in your project source file (C, C++, etc) located in `src` folder
by including it, with the C preprocessing directive `#include'.

```src/main.c

#include "header.h"

int main (void)
{
 ...
}
```

Including a header file produces the same results as copying the header file
into each source file that needs it. Such copying would be time-consuming
and error-prone. With a header file, the related declarations appear
in only one place. If they need to be changed, they can be changed in one
place, and programs that include the header file will automatically use the
new version when next recompiled. The header file eliminates the labor of
finding and changing all the copies as well as the risk that a failure to
find one copy will result in inconsistencies within a program.

In C, the convention is to give header files names that end with `.h'.
````
